snippet.textDisplay:
안무가 정말 좋아요. 자아가 그림자에 짓눌림 — 자아가 그림자를 떨쳐내려 애씀 — 그림자를 떨쳐내고 혼자 날개짓 성공 — 외로워진 자아는 더 깊은 내면 속으로 스스로 걸어 들어감 — 더 깊은 곳에서도 어김없이 자아를 기다리고 있는 그림자 — 한층 더 공격적으로 더 세게 자아를 짓누르려는 그림자 — 자아는 지지않고 더 힘껏 그림자를 이겨냄(자아를 공격하는 그림자가 자아와 같은 성을 가진 남성이라는 설정이 흥미로움) — 자아에게 진 그림자는 이제 자아를 따라 모방하듯 움직임 — 그림자는 자아에게 스며들어 날개짓하는 자아를 들어올림—그림자와 자아의 화해, 결국 자아를 더 날아오르게 만드는 토대가 되는 그림자

인간의 내면을 보여주는 듯한 무대도 훌륭합니다. 층을 달리하며 빛이 들어오는 곳과 들어오지 않는 곳, 밝고 어두운 정도가 곳곳마다 다르고, 층마다 더 깊은 심연으로 들어가는 길을 계단으로 표현, 두번째 계단 아래는 아주 어두워 심연의 층이 얼마나 더 깊을지 알 수 없도록 하고, 자아와 그림자를 비추어 볼 수 있는 거울을 바닥의 물로 표현, 빛이 창살처럼 경계선으로 둘러쳐진 감옥 같은 공간(그 안에 경계를 뚫고 나가려는 자와와 그를 막는 그림자를 가두고 있는)

자아가 스스로 날개짓을 하기 시작하면서 점점 줌인 되어 자아가 커지는 모습을 표현한 것, 제 발로 걸어들어간 심연에서 그림자와 싸워 이겨내는 자아의 역동성을 근접해서 잘 잡아낸 것도 좋았습니다.

snippet.textDisplay: real talk, this song hit pretty hard! the boys writing this song about the what it looks like when you feel a disconnect with your passions or fear losing the things that make up such a big part of you -- oof. i feel precisely this way ALL THE TIME about my writing and how when i'm blocked like i have been for so long, i feel like i've lost what connects me to my craft, my art, the one thing i feel like i'm actually GOOD at. but the 'do your thang' refrain and the 'let go of me, let my own feet carry me' line make me feel hopeful that the well is not empty and something that's this big a part of my soul doesn't just die and i'll find that thing again that lights the fire. thank the universe for bts; so HERE for this evolution.

snippet.textDisplay:
because to be really fucking honest? art is TIRING. all forms, in every way. dancing? singing? acting? writing? drawing? etc.... it consumes your whole damn heart and mind and soul, and it's not something you can switch off like a day job. you carry it with you like a second skin.the fact that bts addresses this makes them all the more human and even more admirable. i respect their work so much.and many people take these works SO lightly, because they don't understand what it's like to pluck a piece of your soul and lay it out bare for the world to see.
they see a performer onstage. they see cool costumes. they see doodles. they hear songs.
but that's your heart thereand YET that's not the point of black swan. my main takeaway from the song's message is: it's okay to be tired. it's okay for the passion to flicker low, as long as it doesn't flicker out.black swan is a tribute to all artists out there and that's that.do u know why many artists get so butthurt over the smallest criticism?

because often it’s not just their work you’re nitpicking, it’s what their work represents—the essence of their soul

i know artists are trained to be open to constructive criticism but they feel so very deeply!!!!!

snippet.textDisplay:
When I was a child, my dad used to tell me that I shouldn't hurt any living thing. He explained to me that all living things deserve love and respect because we can all feel pain in some way or another.
On the other hand, my mom always encourages me to help people. She often buys food to give to those who need it. She told me that we were fortunate, and whenever I had the opportunity, I should help other people, regardless of their economic or social context.

I feel proud and grateful to my parents for the lessons I learned with them. However, now that I write this letter, I realize my whole family has influenced me in some way or another.

I still remember seeing my grandfather turning on the recorder to play music and start singing to flowers. I asked him the reason he spoke to the plants. He replied that plants can hear us and feel what you are trying to transmit to them; if you talk to them kindly and treat them well, they will grow beautiful and healthy.
I can tell many beautiful memories of my childhood. They taught me many things, but for some reason, they forgot to tell me that before loving and helping others, I had first to love and respect myself.
Two years ago, I would have thought that was entirely selfish, why would a person put their needs before other people's needs?

As a child, I always distinguished myself for being very dreamy, loving, and empathetic. I liked to give letters to the people I loved most. That little action made me very happy because I felt that in a way, I could communicate my deepest feelings and thoughts.
But as I grew up, I realized that not everyone valued the fact that I gave them all my love, affection, and attention. That broke my heart into a thousand pieces, continually crying because I felt like my heart was rejected by the people I appreciated.
I felt more and more lonely, and in some ways, more rejected. My parents told me that maybe it was my fault because perhaps I gave a lot of love and unfortunately, not all people value that. Someday I would find someone who would love me with the same strength.

I was still a little girl, so I understood the basic idea that my parents tried to teach me. However, I didn't know how not to give people so much love, it was complicated because I was used to it, it was like something automatic in me. Now that I look back, I realize that I stick to the idea that one day a person would come to love me in the same way that I could love.

I can't remember at what moment it happened. At one point in my life, I decided that the best thing for me was to repress and make my ability to give love to others disappear.
I took that part of me and put it in a safety box.
What I didn't know was that I would need that strength to give love, to get out of my own maze of darkness.

In 2017, I began to feel that something was not right in me. However, at that time, I was studying at the university; it was my last year before graduating, so I decided to ignore and continue my daily routine. At least that was what I believed.

There is a date that I will never forget, and that day is January 2, 2018. That day I woke up very early, everything seemed "normal." Suddenly, I began to feel that something wasn't right, it was evident I was starting to feel very unhappy.
I didn't want to be like that, it wasn't right to feel that way, I tried to ignore the feeling, but it didn't work out.

From that moment on, a power struggle began to arise inside of me, I couldn't understand what was happening to me.
Have you ever felt that you are trapped in a labyrinth, and even if you are looking for a way out, you cannot find it? That's how I felt at that moment, the maze was dark, lonely, and cold. I wanted to move forward, but something stopped me from moving my body, I couldn't move.
I wanted someone to help me unless he told me what I had to do, I was very lost and confused.

Four months passed, and I tried to find a way out, but I couldn't see anything. But, something told me to have faith to keep trying.

One day I woke up and felt like an echo inside me. I decided to pay attention to it, the voice came from inside of me and repeated that there was a reason why I was alive, so I decided to look for the answer.

For months I tried to find the answer, it wasn't easy, but I found it.

That voice that spoke within me was the missing piece that I felt was needed in my life. That was the voice of my soul, trying to get attention. But why didn't I recognize her or remember that she existed?

Now that time has passed, I have worked a lot to be able to find myself. I realize that when I was a child, hearing my inner voice gave me a lot of happiness. She was my best friend, but while I was growing, the fear was taking up a lot of space inside from me, at some point, the mind began to dominate me. It was there when I completely forgot to hear my inner voice.

My inner voice was the one who taught me that I had to release my ability to give love from the safety box. However, this time we would make some adjustments, that love had to be first for me and then for others.
I began to understand what that really means.
Have you ever asked yourself this question: Who Am I?
I couldn't see anything in me or at least something that could describe my real being.

I grew up with the idea that there are negative emotions and positive emotions. I always tried not to feel the "negative" emotions because I automatically felt like a wrong person.

Darkness is prohibited in our lives, we unconsciously decide to reject it. We generate anxiety and fear because we do not want to be judged and rejected by our society, the fear of rejection makes us ashamed of ourselves. It can even stop us from believing in our own light.
It took me a lot of work to understand, I accept that the dark side is present in all human beings, even in life.
Sometimes some days are beautiful; others really stink. But, when you stop focusing on the extremes, you can appreciate the whole landscape. You realize that life is fascinating because it is always in balance.
For a long time, I rejected my dark part, I didn't want to see her, much less know her. Without realizing there was a rebound effect.
When I rejected my dark part, I also dismissed other people when I knew their dark part. I tried to live in the light, but I fell into perfection and the unreal, I demanded a lot from myself, but I also demanded it from others.

The day I began to understand and accept duality, I definitely knew peace.

Fear can help us to protect ourselves and be careful in vulnerable situations. However, fear is dangerous, too, because it can dominate our mind without realizing it. I am learning to listen to myself and pay attention to the signals, I don't want to forget again or forget what my soul sounds like. Day by day, I try not to confuse who is talking to me, whether fear or my soul.

After all that I have experienced in recent years, I have realized that coincidences don't exist.

Until 2019, it's when I met BTS.
I must admit that I knew very little about BTS, I knew they were a Kpop group and that they were having a lot of success all over the world. But I hadn't had the opportunity to investigate. Further, I guess it wasn't the right time yet.
One day his speech at the UN appeared on YouTube. After watching that video, I understood the magic of BTS.
From that moment, I identified a lot with the group. However, that video made me more curious about the history, members, and music of BTS.

There is no doubt that you're very talented people; for me, that can't be discussed. However, I would like to thank you for the fact that you are trying to open your heart as much as you can, to show the human part of BTS.
I can't tell you that my life changed when I met BTS, I would be lying to you. However, I can say that your music and words help me keep in touch with my real being. Your songs remind me of the process that I started in 2017 to get to know me, accept myself, and discover myself. Although we don't speak the same language, your songs transmit strong and deep emotions.

That's why I try to write this letter. I can't find another way to thank you. I have no words to express the admiration I feel for BTS for talking about the shadow, ego, person, of self-love. They are quite deep and personal issues. Accepting your darkness can be difficult, but when you do, you start to see giant flashes of light. They may have been told many times, but they are really generating positive changes in the lives of many people.

I wish you much happiness >>>>>
Thank you.

When I was a child, my dad used to tell me that I shouldn't hurt any living thing. He explained to me that all living things deserve love and respect because we can all feel pain in some way or another.
On the other hand, my mom always encourages me to help people. She often buys food to give to those who need it. She told me that we were fortunate, and whenever I had the opportunity, I should help other people, regardless of their economic or social context.

I feel proud and grateful to my parents for the lessons I learned with them. However, now that I write this letter, I realize my whole family has influenced me in some way or another.

I still remember seeing my grandfather turning on the recorder to play music and start singing to flowers. I asked him the reason he spoke to the plants. He replied that plants can hear us and feel what you are trying to transmit to them; if you talk to them kindly and treat them well, they will grow beautiful and healthy.
I can tell many beautiful memories of my childhood. They taught me many things, but for some reason, they forgot to tell me that before loving and helping others, I had first to love and respect myself.
Two years ago, I would have thought that was entirely selfish, why would a person put their needs before other people's needs? 

As a child, I always distinguished myself for being very dreamy, loving, and empathetic. I liked to give letters to the people I loved most. That little action made me very happy because I felt that in a way, I could communicate my deepest feelings and thoughts.
But as I grew up, I realized that not everyone valued the fact that I gave them all my love, affection, and attention. That broke my heart into a thousand pieces, continually crying because I felt like my heart was rejected by the people I appreciated.
I felt more and more lonely, and in some ways, more rejected. My parents told me that maybe it was my fault because perhaps I gave a lot of love and unfortunately, not all people value that. Someday I would find someone who would love me with the same strength.

I was still a little girl, so I understood the basic idea that my parents tried to teach me. However, I didn't know how not to give people so much love, it was complicated because I was used to it, it was like something automatic in me. Now that I look back, I realize that I stick to the idea that one day a person would come to love me in the same way that I could love.
